history.content:
As you said, EE 16A is a major requirement, so I don't see an exception being granted for this. CS juniors and seniors took EE16A this semester. You may want to speak with them to get their perspective on the class. I would also recommend speaking with your CS advisor. 

EE 16A&B are pre-reqs for EE 126 and EE 16A&B or instructor permission are required for EECS 149.

EE126 also isn't an electronics class (it has no EE components to it).

BTW, 16a isn't a tough course at all.
EE126 also isn't an electronics class (it has no EE components to it).

children.subject:
It is quite amusing to see students think that courses that have "EE" labels have something to do with electronics. That is not the case, although I guess it is understandable that someone might think so. 

It is true that the 16 sequence is aimed at freshmen and so it is not exactly the best fit culturally or content-wise for someone who is a senior. (Think what taking 61a as a senior would feel like.) But oh well, this is an unavoidable transient effect.

history.content: I'm going to be a senior CS major and I need to satisfy the EE16a requirement. As I understand the class is actually for freshman. Is it at all acceptable to replace the EE requirement (ee16a) with a (harder) upper division electronics class, such as EECS149 or EE126?
history.subject: Upper div EE as replacement for EE16a
